{{Infobox person | name = Ashley Deans | image = Ashley-deans-cropped.jpg | image_size = 100 px | caption = Ashley Deans | birth_place = | birth_date = | death_date = | death_place = | education = | occupation = Educator, physicist, researcher, author, politician | title = Dr. | spouse = | parents = | children = | nationality =Canadian American | website = }}
'''Ashley Deans''' is a Canadian physicist, educator, researcher, author and politician. He is Professor of Education and Physics at [[Maharishi University of Management]], Executive Director of [[Maharishi School of the Age of Enlightenment]] (MSAE)<ref name=MUM/> and former president of the [[Natural Law Party of Ontario]].{{citation needed|date=October 2013}} Deans is Director of International Programs<ref name=MUM/> and a member of the Board of Advisors of the [[David Lynch Foundation]].<ref name=dlf>[http://www.davidlynchfoundation.org/about-us.html About] at the DLF website.</ref>
==Education== Deans graduated with a B.Sc. and an [[Associate of the Royal College of Science|ARCS]] from the [[Imperial College London]] in 1969 and has a Ph.D in Upper Atmospheric Physics from [[York University]], [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]], Canada, where he was a [[National Research Council of Canada]] Graduate Fellow. He was awarded a Doctorate of World Peace from [[MERU, Holland#Maharishi European Research University|Maharishi European Research University]] (MERU) in 2005.<ref name=MUM>{{cite web|title=MUM faculty page |url=http://www.mum.edu/faculty/deans_ashley.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64pOICObE?url=http://www.mum.edu/faculty/deans_ashley.html |archivedate=January 20, 2012 |publisher=Maharishi University of Management |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref>
==Career== <!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Ashley-deans-jane-deans-david-lynch.jpg|thumb|right|Deans (left) and wife Jane (middle), with [[David Lynch]] (right)]] --> Deans served as Headmaster of [[Maharishi School of the Age of Enlightenment]] (MSAE) in Fairfield, Iowa for 15 years. He later became its Executive Director and a member of the Board of Directors.<ref name=MUM/><ref>[http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2006/04/09/sunday/main1483025.shtml. "Getting Into Our Minds"] February 11, 2009, CBS News</ref><ref>[http://www.maharishischooliowa.org/about-us/governance/ Governance] Maharishi School of the Age of Enlightenment web site</ref> Deans undertook a worldwide speaking tour {{when|date=April 2012}} to promote MSAE's style of "consciousness-based education" and the practice of the [[Transcendental Meditation technique]] (TM) for schools.<ref>[http://telegraphjournal.canadaeast.com/rss/article/672410 Telegraph Journal: Meditation back to ease stress in schools] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716102441/http://telegraphjournal.canadaeast.com/rss/article/672410 |date=July 16, 2011 }}</ref> He gave presentations in six cities in Canada in 2006.<ref>{{cite news|title=Yogic flyers want schoolkids to say 'om'|first=Graeme |last=Hamilton|work=National Post|location=Don Mills, Ont.|date=May 16, 2006|page=A.2 | url=http://www.canada.com/nationalpost/news/story.html?id=dca535ce-afc5-418e-9b20-f160b0ebc4a9&k=70931}}</ref> Deans is a member of the advisory board for the [[David Lynch Foundation]].<ref name=dlf/>
In 1976, while at the Centre for Research in Experimental Space Science, York University, in Ontario, Deans published a paper on [[Aurora (astronomy)|aurora]] emissions (in ''Journal of Geophysical Research'', 1976).<ref name="agu.org">[http://www.agu.org/pubs/crossref/1976/JA081i034p06227.shtml Journal of Geophysical Research, 81(34), 6227-6232]</ref> Deans co-authored a paper on [[supersymmetry]] theory (in ''Physics Letters B'', 1993) with [[John Hagelin]] at Maharishi University of Management in 1993.<ref name="Physical Review Online Archive">[http://prola.aps.org/abstract/PRL/v71/i26/p4291_1 Physical Review Online Archive]</ref> As the Associate Professor of Physics at Maharishi University of Management in 1996, he co-authored a paper on the [[Maharishi Effect]] that was published in ''Psychology, Crime, and Law''.<ref name="informaworld.com">[http://www.informaworld.com/smpp/content~db=all~content=a789209348?words=ashley,deans Psychology, Crime, and Law, Volume 2, Issue 3, 1996]</ref>
Deans ran in the [[Trinity Spadina]] riding for the federal Natural Law Party of Canada in 1993, 1997,<ref name="Spadina"/> and 2000.<ref>[http://www.elections.ca/scripts/edwa301_historical/Default.asp?L=E&Page=PastResults&ED=35091 Elections Canada Electoral District Results: Trinity Spadina] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019143952/http://www.elections.ca/scripts/edwa301_historical/Default.asp?L=E&Page=PastResults&ED=35091 |date=2013-10-19 }}</ref> His best result was in 1993, when he received 1% of the vote.<ref name="Spadina">{{cite web|title=History of Federal Ridings since 1867: TRINITY--SPADINA, Ontario (1987 - )|url=http://www2.parl.gc.ca/Sites/LOP/HFER/hfer.asp?Language=E&Search=Det&rid=971&Include=|publisher=Parliament of Canada|accessdate=October 7, 2010}}</ref> He promised "heaven on earth" if elected.<ref>{{cite news|title=That yogic flying really livens up a party: In B.C., almost 10,000 voters chose the Natural Law party in the 1993 federal election. Series: The 6.5 Per centers|first=Frances |last=Bula|work=The Vancouver Sun|date=May 24, 1997|page=A.4}}</ref>{{quotation needed|date=October 2013}} Deans was the founding president of the [[Natural Law Party of Ontario]] (NLP), which he said championed the Maharishi's policies.<ref name=Sornberger/> He was also deputy leader of the federal [[Natural Law Party of Canada]],<ref name=Globe/>{{quotation needed|date=October 2013}} and was its leader in 2000.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Media Advisory - Natural Law Party Leader Available for Wrap-Up Comment on Election 2000|agency=Canada NewsWire|location=Ottawa|date=Nov 23, 2000}}</ref> His party's platform included the formation of a group of 7,000 meditators practicing the [[TM-Sidhi program]], also known as "Yogic Flying".<ref name=Sornberger>{{cite news|title=THE UPSTART PARTIES; New groups have their own ideas about changing the way we do politics|first=Joe |last=Sornberger|work=The Ottawa Citizen|date=April 17, 1993|page=B.3}}</ref>{{quotation needed|date=October 2013}} The party criticized the south-facing doors of the [[Centre Block|parliament building]],<ref name=Globe>{{cite news|title=ELECTION '97 In brief The Tories' quick response|work=The Globe and Mail|location=Toronto, Ont.|date=April 30, 1997|page=A.8}}</ref>{{quotation needed|date=October 2013}} and the south-facing border crossings with the United States, both of which were said be inauspicious.<ref>{{cite news|title=Election '97 Natural Law campaign off to usual flying start Fringe party urges Canadians to stop using entrances that face south, west|first=Chad |last=Skelton|work=The Globe and Mail|date=May 12, 1997|page=A.6}}</ref>{{quotation needed|date=October 2013}}
During the 2000 federal election campaign, Deans said "more than 600 scientific studies backed up our claims that meditation activities reduce crime, disease and stress while improving the economy in areas where it is practised".<ref>LaFleche, Grant: Natural Law deputy floats in for visit. ''St. Catharines Standard'', November 23, 2000</ref>{{quotation needed|date=October 2013}} At an all-parties debate that year, he said of [[climate change]]: "All of the outside influences that are damaging Canada today are coming because of incoherence in our collective consciousness. As a physicist, I can speak of the [[Meisner Effect]], where a magnetic field can penetrate a metal, unless the electrons in the metal are highly coherent. Then you have a superconductor and that repels the outside influence."<ref>{{cite news|title=Fringe debate features less yelling, better karma|first=Mark |last=MacKinnon|work=The Globe and Mail|date=November 20, 2000|page=A.1}}</ref>{{quotation needed|date=October 2013}}
==Books and publications== Deans published the book: ''A Record of Excellence: The Remarkable Success of Maharishi School of the Age of Enlightenment'' in 2005.<ref name="World Cat">Deans, Ashley (2005) MUM Press [http://www.worldcat.org/title/record-of-excellence-the-remarkable-success-of-maharishi-school-of-the-age-of-enlightenment/oclc/58789878&referer=brief_results Ashely Deans] World Cat, retrieved April 8, 2012</ref> Deans has authored or co-authored several studies in the fields of physics and on the group effect of Transcendental Meditation. According to his bio, his research has been published in the Canadian Journal of Physics, Journal of Geophysical Research, Planetary and Space Science, Track and Field Journal, Medecin Du Quebec, Journal of Crime Psychology and Law, Physics Letters B and Physical Review Letters.<ref>[http://enlightenededucator.typepad.com/about.html Bio] Enlightened Educator.com</ref>
Other publications include: * A Rocket Measurement of the O2(b¹Σ g +-X³Σ g −)(0-0) Atmospheric Band in Aurora, [[Journal of Geophysical Research]] (1976)<ref name="agu.org"/> * Chaotic inflation and cold baryosynthesis in a supersymmetric GUT, [[Physics Letters B]]<ref>{{cite journal|url = http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0370269389908897 | doi=10.1016/0370-2693(89)90889-7 | volume=220 | title=Chaotic inflation and cold baryosynthesis in a supersymmetric gut | year=1989 | journal=Physics Letters B | pages=368–374 | last1 = Connors | first1 = Larry | last2 = Deans | first2 = Ashley J. | last3 = Hagelin | first3 = John S.}}</ref> * Supersymmetry mechanism for naturally small density perturbations and baryogenesis, [[Physical Review Letters]] (1993) <ref name="Physical Review Online Archive"/><ref>[https://archive.is/20120715122438/http://prl.aps.org/abstract/PRL/v71/i26/p4291_1 Supersymmetry mechanism] Physical Review Letters, retrieved April 8, 2012</ref> * The maharishi effect: A model for social improvement. Time series analysis of a phase transition to reduced crime in merseyside metropolitan area, ''Psychology, Crime, and Law'' (1996)<ref name="informaworld.com"/>
