[[File:Haibao en Expo 2008.jpg|250px|right|thumb|Haibao]] '''Haibao''' ({{zh|s=海宝|t=海寶}}), meaning "jewel of the sea", is the [[mascot]] of [[Expo 2010]], which was held in the city of [[Shanghai]], [[China]] from May 1 to October 31, 2010.
==Meaning== [[File:人-seal.svg|100px|right|thumb|The [[Chinese character|character]] 人 in [[seal script]]]] "Hai (海)" means the [[sea]] in Chinese inscribed from the name of the host city, and "Bao (宝,寶)" means the [[treasure]]. Its figure is in the shape of the [[Chinese character]] "Ren (人)" (meaning [[human]]). Haibao was produced by [[Taiwanese people|Taiwanese]] [[designer]] Wu Yong-jian and adopted as the official mascot of the World Expo on December 18, 2007. He was selected out of 26,655 entries as part of an international competition.
== Similarities ==
Some say that Haibao resembles [[Gumby]], the green [[clay]] [[humanoid]] figure shown on American television from the 1950s–'60s.<ref name="jt20100419">{{cite web |url=http://mainichi.jp/select/world/news/20100424k0000e030038000c.html |title=上海万博：また盗作騒ぎ マスコット「ガンビーに似てる」 |publisher=The Mainichi Daily News |date=24 April 2010 |accessdate=24 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100427073210/http://mainichi.jp/select/world/news/20100424k0000e030038000c.html |archivedate=April 27, 2010 |deadurl=yes |df= }} (Japanese)</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mainichi.jp/select/world/news/20100424dde035030059000c.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120714091627/http://mainichi.jp/select/world/news/20100424dde035030059000c.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=14 July 2012 |title=上海万博：マスコットのコピー横行 「そもそも米キャラの盗作」|publisher=The Mainichi Daily News |date=24 April 2010 |accessdate=24 April 2010}} (Japanese)</ref> The expo's secretariat said that it is an original design and they had never heard of Gumby.
It has been noted that, compared to Gumby, Haibao looks far more like a cartoon mascot also named ''Haibao'' from an appliance company, Xinxiang Haibao Electrical Appliance, whose managers are unsure why the Expo would use "almost the same image as our logo", adding that it was "the biggest ever advertising for free."<ref>[http://www.cnngo.com/shanghai/none/haibo-gumcy-face/-391841 Haibao vs Gumby: The copycat charade]</ref><ref>[https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5jWohhdJTE__hZikypszSiP1MEx1AD9FBCOV00 Shanghai Expo designer denies mascot copy of Gumby]</ref>
