{{Expand Spanish |Roy Emile Gereau|date=March 2014}} {{Expand Dutch |Roy Gereau|date=March 2014}}
{{Infobox scientist | name = Roy Emile Gereau | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1947|12|05}} | birth_place = [[Rock Island, Illinois|Rock Island]], [[Illinois]] | death_date = | death_place = | residence = | citizenship = American | nationality = | fields = [[Botany]] | workplaces = | alma_mater = [[University of Iowa]] | doctoral_advisor = | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = [[Liliaceae]] ([[Bomarea]]), Andean [[Caryophyllaceae]], [[Rosaceae]], [[Urticaceae]] | author_abbrev_bot = Gereau | author_abbrev_zoo = | influences = }}
'''Roy Emile Gereau''' (born 1947) is an [[American people|American]] [[botanist]] and [[explorer]].
== Career == Educated at the [[University of Iowa]] and [[Michigan Technological University]] he graduated BA 1969 and taught at Michigan Technological University and Michigan State University (1975-1983), and at the [[Missouri Botanical Garden]], St. Louis, Missouri since 1983, where he has been Assistant Curator since April 2005.<ref>[http://www.missouribotanicalgarden.org/Portals/0/staff/PDFs/gereau/gereaucv.pdf Curriculum Vitae: Roy Emile Gereau]</ref>
He has conducted botanical expeditions in both [[Africa]] ([[Cameroons]], [[Republic of Congo]], [[Ethiopia]], [[Kenya]], [[Madagascar]], [[Tanzania]] and [[Uganda]]) and the [[Americas]] ([[Costa Rica]], [[Guatemala]] and [[Mexico]]).
== Research interests == Gereau has specialised in the Floristics and [[phytogeography]] of eastern Africa, he is also engaged in collaborative studies between [[ethnobotany]] and [[archeology]].
Gereau is noted for his contributions to the study of the [[Ancistrocladaceae]], [[Mimosaceae]] and [[Sapindales]] of Africa.
== Publications == Gereau has publications to his name in journals such as [[Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden]], [[Economic Botany]] and Novon. He also sits on the editorial board of Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden and Novon. Along with Jon C. Lovett, Chris K. Ruffo and James RD Taplin, he is the author of ''Field Guide to the Moist Forest Trees of Tanzania'', which was published in 2006. He participates in the [[Flora Mesoamericana]], a collaborative project that is aimed at identifying and describing the vascular plants of [[Mesoamerica]]. {{botanist|Gereau|Gereau, Roy Emile}}
